Below is a **cost model for the GWLB-based traffic-mirroring design** you shared, sized for **3 AWS accounts √ó 2 VPCs each = 6 source VPCs**, feeding a **central GWLB in a monitoring (networking) account** and **two ExtraHop packet sensors (EC2) behind the GWLB**. This excludes any ExtraHop licensing.

I‚Äôve used current public pricing references and made explicit, tunable assumptions so you can adjust later.

---

# Assumptions (tunable)

* **Region:** us-east-1 (N. Virginia).
* **Source VPCs:** 6 (Primary/DR in each of 3 accounts).
* **AZ coverage for endpoints:** 2 AZs per VPC ‚áí **12 GWLBE endpoints**.
* **Mirrored ENIs per VPC:** 4 (e.g., App nodes, ALB targets, EKS nodes, DB tier) ‚áí **24 mirrored ENIs** total.
* **Mirrored volume (total across all VPCs):** **\~1.2 TB/month** (‚âà 1,229 GB).
* **Sensors (EC2):** 2 √ó **c5.xlarge** on-demand, 24√ó7 (you can right-size later).
* **GWLB:** 1 GWLB spanning 2 AZs in monitoring account.
* **Data path:** GWLBE (PrivateLink) ‚Üí GWLB ‚Üí sensor targets in same region.

---

# Unit prices used (key sources)

* **EC2 c5.xlarge on-demand** ‚âà **\$0.17/hr** in us-east-1. ([Vantage][1])
* **VPC Traffic Mirroring:** **\$0.015/hr per mirrored ENI** **+ \$0.015/GB** processed. ([Amazon Web Services, Inc.][2])
* **Gateway Load Balancer (GWLB):** billed **per GWLB-hour + per GLCU-hour** (capacity units). AWS examples show typical totals; here I model **\$0.0168/GWLB-hr** and **\$0.004/GLCU-hr** for bytes-driven usage (see ELB pricing examples and public write-ups; regional rates vary). ([Amazon Web Services, Inc.][3])
* **Gateway Load Balancer Endpoint (GWLBE / PrivateLink):** **\$0.01/endpoint-hr + \$0.0035/GB** data processed. ([CloudFix][4])

> üìù GWLB/GWLBE pricing is officially stated as ‚Äúper hour + per (G)LCU or per-GB‚Äù. The dollar figures above reflect current example values and widely cited us-east-1 rates; always verify in the **AWS ELB** and **PrivateLink** pricing pages for your region. ([Amazon Web Services, Inc.][3])

---

# Cost Estimate (AWS only)

| Resource / Description                                                                            |  Monthly Cost (USD) |     Annual Cost (USD) |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------: | --------------------: |
| **EC2 ‚Äì ExtraHop sensors**: 2 √ó c5.xlarge, 730 hr/mo √ó \$0.17/hr                                  |        **\$248.20** |        **\$2,978.40** |
| **Traffic Mirroring ‚Äì ENI hourly**: 24 ENIs √ó 730 hr √ó \$0.015/hr                                 |        **\$262.80** |        **\$3,153.60** |
| **Traffic Mirroring ‚Äì data processed**: 1,229 GB √ó \$0.015/GB                                     |         **\$18.44** |          **\$221.22** |
| **GWLBE ‚Äì hourly**: 12 endpoints √ó 730 hr √ó \$0.01/hr                                             |         **\$87.60** |        **\$1,051.20** |
| **GWLBE ‚Äì data processed**: 1,229 GB √ó \$0.0035/GB                                                |          **\$4.30** |           **\$51.62** |
| **GWLB ‚Äì hourly**: 730 hr √ó \$0.0168/hr                                                           |         **\$12.26** |          **\$147.17** |
| **GWLB ‚Äì capacity (GLCU) bytes dimension**: (1,229 GB / 730 hr ‚âà 1.68 GLCU-hr) √ó \$0.004 √ó 730 hr |          **\$4.91** |           **\$58.87** |
| **Estimated Total**                                                                               | **\~\$638.51 / mo** | **\~\$7,662.08 / yr** |

---

## What drives this cost most?

1. **Mirrored ENI-hours** ‚Äì If you mirror many ENIs per VPC, this dominates. Reducing mirrored sources (e.g., mirror only critical subnets or EKS worker nodes) saves quickly. ([CloudZero][5])
2. **EC2 sensor sizing/count** ‚Äì Right-sizing or Savings Plans can materially reduce the \$248/mo line. ([Vantage][1])
3. **Endpoint footprint** ‚Äì Two AZs per VPC gives resilience but doubles endpoint-hours. If a VPC is single-AZ, you can halve GWLBE hourly. ([Amazon Web Services, Inc.][6])

---

## Sensitivity / ‚Äúwhat-if‚Äù knobs (useful for leadership slides)

* **Change mirrored volume:** Every **+1 TB/mo** adds about **+\$15 (traffic mirroring)** and **+\$3.5 (GWLBE)**; GWLB GLCU adds a few more dollars depending on bytes/flow mix. ([CloudZero][5])
* **Mirrored ENIs:** Each additional mirrored ENI adds **\$10.95/mo** (0.015√ó730). ([CloudZero][5])
* **Fewer endpoints:** Removing one GWLBE saves **\$7.30/mo** (endpoint-hour) plus its share of per-GB. ([Amazon Web Services, Inc.][6])
* **Sensor instance type:** Dropping to **c5.large** (\~\$0.085/hr) halves EC2 to \~**\$124/mo**; moving to **c5.2xlarge** doubles it. ([Amazon Web Services, Inc.][7])

---

## Notes & caveats (read before you share)

* **Exact GWLB/GLCU math**: GWLB bills on the max of dimensions (flows/sec, active flows, processed bytes). I used a **bytes-dominant** case to keep it simple; if your traffic profile has many short flows, GLCU may rise. Validate with CloudWatch ELB metrics during PoC. ([Amazon Web Services, Inc.][3])
* **Data transfer**: Intra-region PrivateLink/GWLBE pricing already covers endpoint processing. If traffic crosses AZs or attaches via TGW instead, add those lines separately (TGW: \$0.05/attachment-hr + \$0.02/GB). ([AWS Static][8])
* **Region variance**: Rates differ by region; this model uses commonly cited us-east-1 values and AWS examples. Always re-check the **ELB** and **PrivateLink** pricing pages before finalizing. ([Amazon Web Services, Inc.][3])

